2026-04-16 12:38:35 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module relay contacts / series path to output'] hypothesis_explanation='The control module receives a correct 12 V supply at its input (≈11.99 V with correct polarity), but only ≈0.36 V appears at the output pair that feeds the load module. The lamp is therefore unlit now, and its former 20 s / 0.5 s flicker is no longer seen. Adjusting the timing potentiometer has no effect, which suggests that the sensor/logic may still be powered but the power path from input to output is not being properly closed. \n\nGiven the module architecture, the only element between the control input and output high side in normal operation is the relay (and possibly its PCB traces / solder joints / connector). A stuck‑open or high‑resistance relay contact, or an open circuit in that series path, would produce the measured small residual voltage (~0.36 V from leakage or internal circuitry) instead of a solid 12 V, independent of timing potentiometer adjustments. The steady 0 V at the negative side shows the return path is intact.\n\nTherefore the most probable root cause is a failed series path through the relay contacts (or their immediate connections) inside the control module. Replacing/repairing the relay/contact circuitry in the control module should restore a solid 12 V at the output and normal lamp operation.'
