2026-04-16 12:40:59 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module output indicator LED and its series resistor network (including any parallel sense path loading the output)'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show ~12 V at the relay common and at the relay contact that should feed the output, but only ~0.36 V at the control module Output Cable (+) relative to battery negative. The negative return path is good (0 V), the relay coil is correctly driven, downstream load‑module components and cabling test nominal, and both an internal short of the Output (+) to 0 V and an open/high‑resistance joint between relay contact and cable have been experimentally ruled out.\n\nThe only remaining element that can plausibly pull the output node down to ~0.36 V while still allowing the meter to see a small differential between the two output cables is an internal load within the control module tied between the output (+) node and the negative rail—most likely the switched‑cables indicator LED and its series resistor (or a parallel sense path associated with it). A failed or mis‑wired LED/resistor network (for example, wrong value, partial short, or incorrect connection directly between the relay output pad and ground instead of to the input side) would clamp the relay output node to a few hundred millivolts, explaining:\n- why ~11.99 V is present at the relay’s supply side and at its common contact,\n- why the relay coil drive and sensor node voltages are normal,\n- why the output cable and connector themselves measure only ~0.36 V relative to ground and never rise to 12 V, and\n- why disconnecting the load module does not change the behavior.\n\nTherefore the root cause is a fault in the control module’s output indicator LED / series resistor network (or its immediate wiring) that excessively loads the relay output node to ~0.36 V and prevents the lamps from receiving 12 V.'
