2026-04-16 12:41:17 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module output cable (+) and control module output cable (−) swapped at the relay / PCB side'] hypothesis_explanation='All tested components (relay contacts and coil, indicator network, PCB traces to the relay, negative return, load module wiring and lamps, and the physical mating of control‑output to load‑input at both ends) have been found good. Yet we consistently see ~12 V on the relay output pad relative to battery negative, while the control Output Cable (+) itself sits around 0.36 V and never rises to 12 V, and the output‑pair differential is ~0.36 V. That combination implies that the cable labeled as Output (+) is not actually connected to the relay’s high side, nor directly shorted to ground; instead it is tied to the low‑side node that sits at about 0.36 V above ground (the relay other terminal / sense node), giving the observed readings.\n\nGiven that the PCB traces, relay contacts, and cable/connector hardware have each been ruled out as faulty, the remaining credible fault is a configuration/wiring error internal to the control module: the two output conductors are cross‑connected at the module PCB/relay side so that the conductor marked/labeled as (+) is actually soldered/crimped to the relay low node (≈0.36 V) and the one marked/labeled as (−) is attached to the relay high node (≈12 V) or input positive node. Because the external cabling from control module to load module is correctly "+ to +" and "− to −", the load module ends up seeing roughly 0.36 V on its supposed "+" input and 0 V on its "−" input, which is insufficient to forward‑bias the load‑module protection diode or light the lamps. This internal swap explains: (1) 12 V present at the relay output pad but not on the cable labeled (+); (2) about 0.36 V measured between the two output cables; and (3) lack of effect from adjusting timing/sensitivity, since the relay is actually energizing but its output is not correctly routed to the true + conductor. The root cause is therefore a mis‑termination / swapped connection of the Output (+) and Output (−) conductors to the relay/PCB inside the control module.'
