2026-04-16 12:41:52 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module output cable (+) insulation / jacket damage causing multi‑point short', 'bundle region where control output (+), control input (+), and the negative leads run together (harness or inside box)'] hypothesis_explanation='The ohmmeter test shows Control Output Cable (+) is almost shorted to Control Input (+) (~0.11 Ω) and has low‑resistance paths to both negatives (~1.3–1.4 Ω). This establishes a resistive mesh tying the output positive to the rest of the wiring bundle. Yet internal PCB tests have repeatedly ruled out a short or mis‑wiring on the board, relay, and connector terminations themselves, and replacing the relay path, output connector, and indicator network produced no change.\n\nTherefore, the only remaining plausible location for these low‑Ohm connections is in the cable run itself (or where the cables are bundled/strained as they enter or exit the module): damaged insulation or crushed cable allowing the copper of the Output (+) conductor to contact the Input (+) conductor solidly, and also to touch or partially carbon‑track to one or both negative conductors.\n\nThat fault explains all observations:\n- Output (+) being effectively shorted to Input (+) clamps the output node to a voltage determined by the internal LED/resistor network and the external resistive paths, producing the ~0.36 V seen under load.\n- The ~0.36 V remains even when the PCB/relay side is disconnected, proving that this voltage is imposed by the cabling fault itself, not by the control electronics.\n- The load module has tested nominal, so the abnormal low‑resistance network must lie between the control module PCB pad and the far end of the Output (+) cable, i.e., in the cable or its immediate harness region.\n\nThus, the root cause is a damaged Control Output Cable (+) with compromised insulation leading to unintended multi‑point shorts within the harness, and this cable (or the affected harness section) should be replaced.'
