2026-04-16 12:42:10 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module PCB / wiring topology tying Output Cable (+) permanently to Input Cable (+) (design / documentation error, not damage)'] hypothesis_explanation='All tests show that:\n- The relay contact on the control PCB has ~12 V on the common (input) side and ~0.36 V on the other contact and on the Output Cable (+) when referenced to battery negative.\n- With the load disconnected, Output Cable (+) is low‑ohmic to Input (+) (~0.11 Ω), to Output (−) (~1.4 Ω) and to Input (−) (~1.3 Ω).\n- Disconnecting Output (+) from the PCB does not remove the ~0.36 V level; it floats to the same value via its resistive network to the rest of the control‑module nodes.\n- Physical cable/connector damage, swapped leads, shorts in the harness, and the output LED network have all been ruled out by prior targeted replacements.\n\nThese measurements are not compatible with a single insulation fault or contact fault confined to one component: Output (+) is *intentionally* wired into the internal sensing/indicator network so that it is hard‑tied (through low‑value resistances) to Input (+) and the negative rail. That produces the tested resistances and the ~0.36 V equilibrium with a high‑impedance meter when the relay’s high‑side contact is at 12 V but not actually connected to the external output node.\n\nGiven that multiple repair attempts have confirmed that the relay contacts, traces, connectors, harness, and indicator LED network are not damaged, the only consistent explanation is that the control module’s PCB/wiring is built according to a different topology than the documented one: the pad that was assumed to be the relay’s switched output is in fact a node of an internal sensing/divider network permanently tied to Input (+), and the Output Cable (+) is soldered there by design. In other words, the module is *mis‑designed / mis‑documented* rather than physically faulty, so the external Output (+) can never receive the full 12 V feed needed to drive the load.\n\nThus the root cause of the lamp never lighting (and the odd 0.36 V behavior) is a configuration/design error inside the control module PCB: Output Cable (+) is permanently tied into the internal network instead of being connected to the true relay output node, preventing 12 V from reaching the load under any condition.'
