2026-04-16 12:42:39 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module battery / source element'] hypothesis_explanation='All investigations have localized the anomaly to a low and slowly varying supply potential (~11.99 V at the control input when lightly loaded, but only ~0.36 V available to drive the load, with the control output (+) effectively tied to the input (+) and also resistively to the negatives). Multiple hypotheses about wiring, relay, PCB traces, output indicators, and cable faults have been ruled out by direct repair attempts.\n\nThe remaining consistent explanation is that the 12 V source itself cannot supply the required current and is exhibiting a high internal resistance or intermittent collapse under load. When the load (lamps plus control electronics) draws current, the source voltage sags down toward a few hundred millivolts, causing the lamps to extinguish and the control circuitry to mis‑bias; as the source recovers (chemical recovery in a failing or nearly‑depleted lithium battery), the voltage slowly rises again, briefly allowing illumination before sagging once more. This behavior produces the observed ~20 s cycle with ~0.5 s on/off transients and the measured low effective voltage at nodes that should otherwise be at 12 V.\n\nNo other discrete module‑level or wiring fault remains that can produce all the measured symptoms while surviving prior targeted replacement attempts, so the root cause is most plausibly the degraded / faulty 12 V battery or its immediate source path inside the power supply module.'
