No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-16 12:43:05 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module relay contact orientation / wiring (COM and NC used instead of COM and NO, or relay symbol functionally inverted)', 'control module sensor/driver logic polarity or threshold configuration (relay driven in opposite sense, holding contacts open under normal conditions)'] hypothesis_explanation='All hardware elements already probed (battery, cabling, PCB traces, output LED network, load module, harness insulation, and even a direct short between control output (+) and other lines) have been ruled out as faulty by replacement attempts and tests. Yet the measured behavior is that the relay coil is being driven (12 V across it) while the output node remains near 0.36 V and no 12 V ever appears on the output cable (+). The negative return is sound, and there is no actual short or high‑resistance fault found between the relay output pad and the cable.\n\nThis combination of facts is most consistent not with a damaged component, but with a configuration/wiring error of the relay contacts relative to the intended schematic: the PCB or wiring may be using the COM and NC (normally‑closed) terminals, or the relay symbol/function may be inverted with respect to the driver logic. In that case, when the sensor/driver energizes the relay coil (which we observe as 12 V across it), the contact *opens* the path to the output instead of closing it, leaving the output node floating and clamped only at a small common‑mode potential (~0.36 V) produced by the surrounding bias network. Because the system and service agent have treated the relay contacts and series path as electrically sound, but not their orientation and usage, previous “repair/replace” actions on the relay hardware itself would not change this misconfiguration.\n\nThus the fault is a functional mis‑wiring / mis‑configuration of the relay contact connections or associated driver logic polarity inside the control module, resulting in the relay energizing in the opposite sense to what the rest of the design expects, and preventing the 12 V from ever being delivered to the load output terminals.'
