description: Open the control module access panel. With the system powered, measure the DC voltage across the relay coil while also monitoring the logic/driver node that controls it (if test points are provided). Confirm whether the relay coil ever receives an appropriate drive voltage (~battery level) and whether that drive is steady or cycling. This will determine if the low output voltage is due to a missing or intermittent drive from the sensor/driver circuitry rather than the relay contacts., outcome='Control relay coil shows approximately 12.0 V on its positive side and 0.36 V on its negative side with respect to ground, indicating substantial drive across the coil. Sensor bias resistor shows approximately 12.0 V on its positive side and 0.12 V on its negative side with respect to ground, indicating a similar stable drive level at the sensor/driver node.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=45.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module series path between input positive and relay contact common,
description: With the control module opened, measure DC voltage along the series path from the control‑input positive terminal, through any series indicator LED/resistor and PCB traces, up to the relay’s common contact. Identify the exact node where the voltage drops from ~12 V to ~0.36 V to locate an open or high‑resistance component or trace in that path., outcome='Measured ~12 V at Control Input Cable (+), PSU Green LED Resistor (input side), and Control Relay common contact, with a drop to ~1.29 V across the LED/resistor network and ~0.36 V at the relay’s other contact. No polarity inversion is present in the reported measurements. The control module inspection panel could not be measured because it lacks a measurable affordance.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=110.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Observe -> inter‑module cable connections between control module outputs and load module inputs,
description: Visually inspect how the two output cables from the control module are mated to the two input cables of the load module. Verify whether the 12 V and 0 V lines are cross‑connected or otherwise mis‑plugged (e.g., both 12 V lines tied together or both 0 V lines tied together) rather than forming a single 12 V–0 V series path through the three modules., outcome='The Control Output Cable (+) is only connected to the Load Input Cable (+), with the positive lines tied together at their respective ports. The Control Output Cable (−) is only connected to the Load Input Cable (−), with the negative lines tied together at their respective ports. No POLARITY INVERSION is present in the inspected connections.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=50.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module output negative path / reference node,
description: With the control module open, measure the DC voltage at the control module’s output negative terminal and along its PCB trace back to the control input negative terminal and battery negative. Verify whether the output negative is truly at 0 V, or floating around ~0.36 V relative to battery negative, to detect a high‑resistance or open connection in the negative return path inside the control module or its cabling., outcome='The control output negative, control input negative, and PSU output negative cables all measure essentially 0 V relative to ground, indicating no significant offset or float on the negative return path. The sensor bias resistor shows about 11.99 V across it (11.9873 V on the positive side vs. 0.119 V on the negative side). No POLARITY INVERSION DETECTED in the measured negative cables.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=85.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module output positive node relative to battery negative,
description: With the system powered and the control module open, measure the DC voltage on the relay output contact and on the control‑module output positive terminal, both referenced to the battery negative (0 V). Confirm whether these nodes sit near 12 V or near 0.36 V despite the earlier ~0.36 V differential reading between the two output cables. This will distinguish between an internal low‑voltage drive condition and an external loading/fault at the load module side., outcome='Control relay positive terminal is at ~11.99 V relative to battery negative, and its negative/other terminal is at ~0.36 V. Control Output Cable (+) measures ~0.36 V on both its positive and negative meter leads relative to battery negative.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=40.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> load module input positive path and lamps,
description: Disconnect the load module from the control module. With the system powered and the control module confirmed to have ~12 V on its output positive terminal relative to battery negative, directly measure continuity and resistance from the load module’s input positive terminal through the series diode to each lamp terminal. Also measure resistance from the load module input positive to input negative (with lamps in circuit). This will reveal whether an internal short or mis‑wiring inside the load module is clamping the control output node to ~0.36 V., outcome='Continuity and resistance measurements are nominal for the Load Input Cable (+), Load Input Cable (−), Main Load lamp, and Internal Indicator Lamp. The Load Protection Diode could not be evaluated in resistance/continuity mode because it has no defined resistance parameter. No POLARITY INVERSION DETECTED in the measured cables.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=105.0, cost_breakdown=[('test_continuity', 20.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module output positive cable and connector (open‑circuit verification),
description: With the load module still disconnected, power the system and, using a high‑impedance voltmeter, measure DC voltage directly on the metal of the control module’s Output Cable (+) fast‑connector at both sides of the mated pair (control side pin and its mating half that would go to the load). Then, gently flex/wiggle the Output Cable (+) and its connector while watching the reading. Confirm whether ~12 V ever appears on the actual cable conductor/connector pin, or if it remains near 0.36 V regardless of the 11.99 V present at the relay output pad, indicating an internal open in the crimp/solder joint between relay output and the cable., outcome='Measured voltage on the Control Output Cable (+) is approximately 0.36 V and does not show ~12 V. No polarity inversion detected in the measured cable.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=20.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module output cable (+) isolation from all other nodes,
description: With the control module powered and the load module still disconnected, use an ohmmeter (power off for resistance checks, then confirm with powered DC measurements) to test the Control Output Cable (+) conductor for unintended continuity to: (a) Control Output Cable (−), (b) Control Input (+), (c) Control Input (−)/battery negative, and (d) any nearby metal/shield or enclosure. Then, with power on, momentarily disconnect the Control Output Cable (+) from the PCB/relay output pad (if possible via plug or removable lug) and measure its floating voltage with respect to battery negative to verify whether the ~0.36 V is being imposed from outside the control electronics (e.g., via a partial short to chassis or another node) rather than by the control circuit itself., outcome='Control Output Cable (+) shows a low-resistance connection to Control Output Cable (−) (≈1.41 Ω) and Control Input Cable (−) (≈1.31 Ω), and an almost shorted connection to Control Input Cable (+) (≈0.11 Ω). POLARITY INVERSION DETECTED: Control Output Cable (+) is effectively shorted to Control Input Cable (+), while also having resistive paths to Control Output Cable (−) and Control Input Cable (−). With power on, the floating Control Output Cable (+) still measures ~0.36 V relative to battery negative.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=140.0, cost_breakdown=[('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module sensor‑bias / driver return path,
description: With power off, measure resistance between the sensor‑bias network lower node (the side of the sensor bias resistor that was previously at ~0.12 V) and the main 0 V rail at the control input negative terminal. Then power on and, with reference to battery negative, re‑measure the voltage on that same sensor‑bias lower node and on the relay coil low side while briefly lifting the connection from that node to the relay driver (if separable). Determine whether this node is truly referenced to 0 V through the intended path or is instead connected through an unintended low‑ohmic path into the +12 V network, which would explain the ~0.36 V common‑mode level seen on multiple nodes., outcome='The battery is at 12.0 V relative to its negative terminal, the sensor bias resistor measures nominal 10 kΩ, and its lower node sits at about 0.12 V relative to battery negative while the upper node is at about 11.99 V. The relay coil high side is also at about 11.99 V and its low side is at about 0.36 V relative to battery negative.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=95.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
